# Cursor Rules for Academic Writings Repository

## Language & Style

- Always write British English in documentation (Markdown, etc.) and code comments
- Use British spelling: "optimised", "organised", "colour", "centre", "realise", etc.
- Use British punctuation: single quotes for emphasis, double quotes for direct quotations
- Academic tone: formal, precise, and scholarly language in all documentation

## LaTeX Guidelines

- Use the unified preamble system from `templates/preamble.tex`
- Always define `\templatevariant` before inputting the preamble using `\providecommand`
- Use `\floatcaption{title}{description}` for enhanced figure/table captions
- Follow British academic conventions for citations and references
- Use `natbib` citation style with proper author-year format
- Maintain consistent indentation (2 spaces) in LaTeX files

## File Organisation

- Papers: `01_papers/YYYY/XXX_paper/` structure
- Essays: `02_essays/YYYY/XXX_essay/` structure
- Main LaTeX file should match directory name (e.g., `essay.tex`, `paper.tex`)
- Include `figures/` and `references/` subdirectories
- Use descriptive filenames with underscores, not spaces

## Template Usage

- Essay variant: Single-column, generous margins, for long-form writing
- Paper variant: Two-column support, compact margins, for academic papers
- Always test both variants when modifying the preamble
- Document any template changes in `templates/README.md`

## Code Quality

- Comment complex LaTeX commands and custom macros
- Use semantic section markers (`% ! # MARK: Section Name`)
- Keep lines under 100 characters where possible
- Remove generated files (.aux, .log, .synctex.gz, etc.) from version control
- Use the pre-configured `listings` environment for all code blocks to ensure consistent styling.

## Documentation Standards

- Update main README.md when adding new papers/essays
- Include publication dates, DOIs, and citation information
- Maintain clear, comprehensive documentation for template usage
- Use proper markdown formatting with British spelling

## Version Control

- Commit source files (.tex, .bib, .md) but exclude generated files
- Use descriptive commit messages in British English
- Keep template changes separate from content changes
- Tag releases for published works

## Bibliography & Citations

- Use BibTeX with custom APA style (`templates/apa.bst`)
- Maintain separate `.bib` files in `references/` directories
- Follow British academic citation conventions
- Ensure all citations are properly formatted and accessible
